Happy Thursday, everyone! 
As we step closer to the weekend, let's take a moment to reflect and embrace the gifts we have. Each of us holds unique strengths and talents—let's use them to create, inspire, and uplift.
Remember, life is a constant journey of learning. Let's appreciate the wisdom and insights others bring into our lives. There’s so much to gain from listening, observing, and growing together.
Gratitude is the best attitude! Being thankful for what we have can transform our outlook and bring positivity into our daily lives.
Lastly, stay focused and keep moving forward towards your goals. Every small step you take is progress. Believe in yourself, stay motivated, and make today amazing!

Dear Young/Aspiring Professional, that HUNGER is your greatest asset,

Never lose it 

It is like a driving force (picture it this way, the way Vampires thirst for blood)

It is your badge of honour. It gives you grit, determination and the kind of URGENCY that sets you apart.

HUNGER is what keeps you going in the face of Challenges.

Be it in finances, opportunities or support

You get creative, turning "less" into "enough."

You find ways to solve problems with what you have.

You learn early on that success isn’t handed out freely, it is EARNED.

You show up, work hard and prove your worth, time and again. It’s a lesson that sticks with you and drives how you approach every goal, every project, every opportunity.

When the odds aren’t in your favor, discipline becomes your greatest ally. The world doesn’t wait, so you don’t either. You push harder, work smarter and adapt faster.

And through it all, you remain humble but hungry; grounded by where you’ve been but fueled by where you’re going.

Your journey, no matter how tough, doesn’t limit you. It prepares you. It refines your character, sharpens your skills and builds a foundation for your future success.

Have you ever felt like your struggles make you less qualified or less deserving?

Angelique Letizia
Angelique Letizia
posts.content:
What if I knew then what I know now? 

If you've ever wished you could run your hands through the river of time, catching fragments of the life you've already lived, then you’ve felt the ache of avenoir.

Avenoir is one of those hauntingly beautiful words from the Dictionary of Obscure Sorrows — the bittersweet desire to see where you’ve been, to watch your past unfold before you like a film, scene by scene.

Imagine you are standing at the edge of your timeline. What would you say to the younger versions of yourself—the dreamer, the risk-taker, the heartbroken?

Would you cheer them on, warn them, or simply watch, mesmerized by the unfolding story of your life?

The ache of avenoir—longing to look back and rewrite our story with the wisdom we’ve gained in the present—can be overwhelming.

However, if we didn’t experience both sides of the polarity spectrum, how would we truly appreciate the human experience?

The grand design of the universe is no accident. In this third-dimensional reality, where time and space are our constructs, we experience life in a linear fashion.

Each moment builds on the last, forcing us to move forward, whether we’re ready or not. While quantum physics reveals a reality where all timelines run concurrently, we live through the lens of time, experiencing life step by step in the physical for reasons known only to the forces that set this world in motion billions of years ago.

We may long for the clarity of hindsight at the moment, but without the lessons learned through pain, joy, failure, and triumph, the wisdom we cherish now simply wouldn’t exist.

Despite what some may say, this linear journey is not a punishment; it’s a gift. A chance to evolve in ways only the limitations of time can teach us.

Therefore, if you find yourself longing for a do-over, remember this: the heartbreaks taught you about the power of love, the mistakes showed you the grace of humility, and the moments of triumph proved you’re capable of anything and everything you set your mind to.

So, the next time you feel the pull of avenoir, remember that the story behind you is as it's meant to be. And like any great tale, perhaps it’s here to teach us that life isn’t meant to be perfect—it’s meant to be lived.

Keep Shining ⭐
©Angelique Letizia

posts.content:
BIG BULLIES, SMALL... 

Wanted to share a small incident from our building's clubhouse today with our son, Risshan. Most will know him from his big singing voice, bigger smile.

Being on the autism spectrum, social communication is often an issue. He has experienced bullying on several occasions, usually by kids who didn't know better, *until* they were explained. So someone *always* accompanies him. Of course, there are also some wonderful, kids and adults who go _out of their way_ to be kind to him.

Today wasn't that day.

He plays squash every Tue/ Thu. But given his attention-deficit, a lot of time goes standing/ twitching... his tool to calm his social anxiety. But on OUR booking time.

He was accompanied by his grandmother today when another gentleman claimed he had a booking [he very well knew, he didn't, and the guard showed him ours], so he then proceeded to ask her to ask Rissh to step out as, "he's anyway doing timepass".
And then with a couple other folks, wanted to go in to play along "so he can learn".

Given the crap network, grandma couldn't reach me to intervene but fortunately she told them off. After which they *grudgingly* went away.

I guess it takes all kinds to make this world [and our society] the place it is. Fortunately the kind ones outnumber the others.

I run free sessions on inclusion. And time spent with Rissh could teach them a thing or two on kindness. Here's wishing them a happy 2025 [and may their lack of awareness/ acceptance/ sensitivity get, erm, squash-ed].

#


Ps: I'm so proud of my self-restraint, with both, my words and actions. My thoughts, however... BWUHAHAHAAHAHAHAHAA!

The snow that blankets our little Ozark enclave, about five inches of it, feels like a gentle reminder from Mother Nature to slow down. 

Like the icicles forming on the bluffs, life can be beautiful when we allow it to freeze for a moment, not rushing to melt into the next task.

A cue to pause, breathe and not overwork ourselves. Appreciating the stillness before the world moves on.

I hope this weekend allows you to flourish in respite.

posts.content:
You don’t get paid what you deserve.
You get paid what you negotiate:

Glassdoor: 54% of Americans didn’t negotiate their most recent salary.

Salary negotiations can be daunting.
Most candidates don’t negotiate because they’re thinking:

 "They'll pull the offer. Can't risk it in this market."
 "After my last job I'll take anything."
 "Prove first, ask later. Right?"

Don’t let fear hold you back from getting your worth.

Here’s how:

1/ Before the Discussion
↳ Keep your current salary private.
↳ Secure offers from other companies.
↳ Research the standard pay range for your role and experience.
↳ Your compensation includes perks and benefits too - stay updated on them.

2/ During the Discussion
↳ Highlight the skills you bring to the table.
↳ Wait for them to make the move.
↳ Start high - aim for the top of the range.

3/ After the Discussion
↳ Follow up in writing to confirm details.
↳ Read the fine print carefully - review and clarify.
↳ Be ready to walk if the offer doesn’t meet your needs.

Don’t avoid negotiation out of fear.
It isn’t just a career skill - it’s a life skill.

P.S. What’s your top tip for negotiating your salary?
